            <div class="col-md-6">  
<p>Hope you're finding my portfolio interesting - would be good to hear from you (<a href="mailto:chris.d@theasi.co?Subject=From%20my%20site" target="_top">chris.d@theasi.co</a>).  Otherwise, <a href="http://images.google.com/search?tbm=isch&q=cat">cat pictures</a>!<sup><a href="#fn1" id="ref1">1</a></sup>  </p>

<p>(<a href="http://uk.linkedin.com/pub/chris-davie/7a/54b/a37">My linkedin</a>, if you're here for that.<sup><a href="#fn2" id="ref2">2</a></sup>  Better than a CV, right?)  </p>

<p>I've recently started as a Data Science consultant, after finishing my PhD in computational physics at Imperial College London. My experience includes d3, MySQL, statistical modelling, Google Analytics, Python, Matlab and C++.</p>

<p>I hope my portfolio shows I enjoy using tools to find out about underlying patterns and behaviour in complex systems.  (This seems to translate to "extracting insight" in data science language.)  I also really enjoy when this insight gets used, helping people make decisions.  </p>

<p>I also hope my portfolio shows an ongoing tendency to build solutions to pretty complicated problems and see them (often!) through to completion.<sup><a href="#fn3" id="ref3">3</a></sup>  </p>

<p>This preference for building solutions over tools development means I aim for the more efficient, well established solutions.  I've done algorithm development and parallelisation during my PhD when I was doing something new, or it needed to be fast, but if there's a library out there I'll try and use it.</p>

<p>I could go on, but that's probably enough.  Thanks for stopping by!</p>

<p><sup id="fn1">1. My boss and I disagree about cat pictures on the internet.  They are quite clearly the single best thing on the internet, and when I say things like that she looks at me scornfully.  She is otherwise pretty sane.<a href="#ref1" title="Jump back to footnote 1 in the text.">↩</a></sup></p>

<p><sup id="fn2">2. I do data science in return for money.  If you need some data science done and have some money, we might be able to work something out.<a href="#ref2" title="Jump back to footnote 2 in the text.">↩</a></sup></p>

<p><sup id="fn3">3. I've often wondered if what makes people good at maths and coding is mostly a higher intrinsic pain threshold for debugging.<a href="#ref3" title="Jump back to footnote 3 in the text.">↩</a></sup></p>
